=========================================================
Templates and Static Variables ⭐⭐⭐⭐
=========================================================

Key Rule
--------

Each template instantiation gets its OWN copy of static variables.

This applies to:

✓ Function Templates
✓ Class Templates

Compiler treats every template instantiation as a completely
different function/class.

=========================================================
1. Function Template and Static Variables
=========================================================

Example

#include<iostream>
using namespace std;

template<typename T>
void fun()
{
    static int count = 0;

    count++;

    cout << count << endl;
}

int main()
{
    fun<int>();
    fun<int>();

    fun<double>();
    fun<double>();
}

Output

1
2
1
2

---------------------------------------------------------
Explanation
---------------------------------------------------------

Compiler creates

void fun<int>()

and

void fun<double>()

Each function has its own static variable.*************

Internally it is similar to

void fun_int()
{
    static int count;
}

void fun_double()
{
    static int count;
}

These are two different functions,
therefore each has its own static variable.

=========================================================
2. Class Template and Static Variables
=========================================================

Example

#include<iostream>
using namespace std;

template<typename T>
class Test
{
public:
    static int count;

    Test()
    {
        count++;
    }
};

template<typename T>
int Test<T>::count = 0;

int main()
{
    Test<int> a;
    Test<int> b;

    Test<double> c;

    cout << Test<int>::count << endl;

    cout << Test<double>::count << endl;
}

Output

2
1

---------------------------------------------------------
Explanation
---------------------------------------------------------

Compiler generates

class Test<int>
{
    static int count;
};

and

class Test<double>
{
    static int count;
};

These are different classes.

Therefore

Test<int>::count

and

Test<double>::count

are different variables.

=========================================================
Memory Visualization
=========================================================

Test<int>

+----------------+
| count = 2      |
+----------------+

----------------------------

Test<double>

+----------------+
| count = 1      |
+----------------+

Both static variables are independent.

=========================================================
Why?
=========================================================

Templates are blueprints.

Compiler creates a separate class/function for every type.

Since they become different generated classes/functions,
their static variables are also separate.

=========================================================
Most Asked Interview Questions
=========================================================

Q. Does every template specialization have its own static variable? ********************

Yes.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. Is static variable shared between Test<int>
and Test<double>?*************************

No.

Each specialization owns its own copy.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. Why?

Because every template instantiation creates a completely
different function/class.

=========================================================
Interview Answer (30 seconds)
=========================================================

"Each template instantiation has its own copy of static variables.
For example, Test<int> and Test<double> are treated as two separate
classes by the compiler, so each specialization has its own static
member. Similarly, function template instantiations like fun<int>()
and fun<double>() each maintain separate local static variables."
